<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate how many deck boards I need?", answer: "Divide the deck width by the board width (including a small gap for drainage) to find the number of boards across. If the deck length exceeds the board length, multiply by the number of runs needed to span the full length. For example, a 16x12 foot deck using 12-foot boards that are 5.5 inches wide needs about 27 boards across and 2 runs if the deck is 16 feet long, totaling 54 boards." },
  { question: "How far apart should deck joists be spaced?", answer: "Standard deck joist spacing is 16 inches on center for most decking materials. Composite decking may require 12-inch spacing at a 45-degree angle or 16-inch spacing for perpendicular installation. Always check the decking manufacturer specifications, as some materials require closer spacing to prevent sagging or bouncing." },
  { question: "How many posts does a deck need?", answer: "Posts are typically spaced every 6 to 8 feet along each beam line. A standard deck has two beam lines (front and back), so a 16-foot-long deck needs about 3 posts on each side, for 6 posts total. Larger decks or those supporting heavy loads like hot tubs may need additional posts. Posts must sit on concrete footings that extend below the frost line." },
  { question: "How many screws do I need for a deck?", answer: "Plan for approximately 350 deck screws per 100 square feet of decking, or about 20 screws per board. Use 2.5-inch or 3-inch coated deck screws for face-fastening. Hidden fastener systems use fewer visible screws but require additional clips. A standard 1-pound box of deck screws contains approximately 75 screws, while a 5-pound box contains about 350." },
  { question: "What size lumber do I need for a deck?", answer: "Decking boards are typically 5/4x6 (actual 1 inch by 5.5 inches). Joists are usually 2x8 or 2x10 depending on span. Beams are doubled 2x8 or 2x10 lumber. Posts are 4x4 for decks under 8 feet high or 6x6 for taller decks. Ledger boards attached to the house should match the joist depth." }
]) %>

